                <head>231. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On March 25 in Rome, representatives of Belgium, France, the Federal Republic of
                    Germany, Italy, Luxembourg, and the Netherlands signed the treaties establishing
                    a European Economic Community (Common Market) and a European Atomic Energy
                    Community (<gloss target="#t_EURATOM1">EURATOM</gloss>). The treaties, which had
                    been drafted in final form by the Intergovernmental Committee in Brussels on
                    March 9, would enter into force after they had been ratified by all six
                    countries. The text of the treaties is printed in <hi rend="italic">American
                        Foreign Policy: Current Documents, 1957</hi>, pages 426–573.</p>
            </div>
